Plan a Field Trip













Exhibitions

Learn about human space flight, World War II aviation, vertical flight, and much more.Exhibitions Currently on View >
Objects on Display

Along with aircraft and spacecraft, you'll find engines, uniforms, models, photographs, and more.Browse Objects on Display >
Science Demonstrations

Discover how things fly or test your own paper airplane design. Demonstrations & Schedules >Reserve one for your school group >
Discovery Stations

Touch a real spacesuit or learn how ancient astronomers studied the stars through active, hands-on activities.More about Discovery Stations >
Daily Tours

Take a tour with one of our knowledgeable guides. Tour Schedule >Reserve a Group Tour >
Observation Tower

Watch planes take off and land at Washington Dulles International Airport and get a 360-degree view of the surrounding area.Learn More about the Donald D. Engen Observation Tower >
 
Learning Labs

These free inquiry-based programs are available to any class. Reservations are required. More about Learning Labs >Reserve a Learning Lab >
IMAX Theater

See films projected on a screen five-stories-high with six-channel digital surround sound. Tickets & Showtimes >
Simulators

Fly jet-age combat sorties in simulators that let you perform 360-degree barrel rolls! More about Simulator Rides >
Restoration Hangar

Watch as our specialists reconstruct, repair, and preserve our rare artifacts. Learn More about the Mary Baker Engen Restoration Hangar >
Smithsonian TechQuest: Flying Circus

Flying Circus is an alternate reality game set in the thrilling era of aviation when daring pilots zoomed across the sky and airplane designers pushed boundaries. 
Learn About Flying Circus >Reserve for groups larger than 15 >
 


More to See and Do 
Looking for more things to do? We offer special programming throughout the year including annual Family Days, star-gazing parties, and evening lectures at both the Museum in Washington, DC and the Udvar-Hazy Center in Chantilly, VA.
















 




