Bob Hoover's Shrike Commander



The museum is still in the process of installing exhibits, but 169 aircraft and 152 large space artifacts are already on display as of May 2012,[1] and plans call for the eventual installation of over 200 aircraft.[8] The current list is maintained at the Objects On Display page of the Smithsonian Institution NASM Collections site.
Events[edit]
A number of events are held at the museum throughout the year.[9] These include lectures, book signings, sleepovers, and events for children. Some of the museum's larger events include Air & Scare for Halloween,[10] an open house,[11] and Innovations in Flight: Family Day and Outdoor Aviation Display.[12]
Media appearances[edit]
The center made its first media appearance in the 2009 film Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen. The center remained open while filming took place, although certain areas were closed.[13] The SR-71 that is on display in the museum was used as Jetfire, a Decepticon who switches sides to become an Autobot, in the film. In the film, it is referred to simply as the National Air and Space Museum.
